England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Trian","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of Italian <b>Toriano</b>: habitational name from Torriano (in Pavia province), or from any of the places called Torriana (for example in Mantova province), or from any of the places called (La) Torre or Torri (for example in Pavia and in Siena province). Compare   Torain  .","History: Schertorio de Toriano/Turriani/Torian married Luna Gioanili in Soglio, Switzerland in 1722, died in Lunenburg County, VA, in 1748."],"variants":[{"name":"Torain","meanings":["Americanized form of Italian <b>Toriano</b> (see   Torian  )."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Trian was born about 1135, in Kent, England as the son of Hugh Trian of Trianstone and Mrs Hugh Trian of Trianstone. He had at least 1 son with Juliana Haudenby. He died after 1199."},"et":{"about 1135–after 1199":"umbes 1135–pärast 1199","1135–1199":"1135–1199","–Female":"Surnud","1160–1207":"1160–1207","–Male":"Surnud","before 1135":"enne 1135","1135":"1135","1199":"1199","about 1135":"umbes 1135","after 1199":"pärast 1199","1160":"1160","1207":"1207","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fi":{"about 1135–after 1199":"noin 1135–1199 jälkeen","1135–1199":"1135–1199","–Female":"Kuollut","1160–1207":"1160–1207","–Male":"Kuollut","before 1135":"ennen vuotta 1135","1135":"1135","1199":"1199","about 1135":"noin 1135","after 1199":"1199 jälkeen","1160":"1160","1207":"1207","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fr":{"about 1135–after 1199":"environ 1135–après 1199","1135–1199":"1135–1199","–Female":"Décédée","1160–1207":"1160–1207","–Male":"Décédé","before 1135":"avant 1135","1135":"1135","1199":"1199","about 1135":"environ 1135","after 1199":"après 1199","1160":"1160","1207":"1207","England":"Angleterre","Kent, England":"Kent, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert de Trian est né environ 1135, à Kent, Angleterre, fils de Hugh Trian of Trianstone et Mrs Hugh Trian of Trianstone. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Juliana Haudenby. Il est décédé après 1199."},"de":{"about 1135–after 1199":"um 1135–nach 1199","1135–1199":"1135–1199","–Female":"Verstorben","1160–1207":"1160–1207","–Male":"Verstorben","b